The paper proposes a pre-training framework for graph neural networks (GNNs) that captures generic graph structural information that is transferable across tasks. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG) as it deals with training GNNs. Additionally, the paper mentions three tasks that the pre-training framework can leverage, which are denoising link reconstruction, centrality score ranking, and cluster preserving. These tasks are related to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper also mentions downstream applications, which could involve natural language processing (cs.CL) and computer vision (cs.CV). Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.SI, cs.CL, and cs.CV, in that order.
